passages.text: Buyback ensures EPS growth is positive

WPR delivered a 1H25 result marginally above its full- year guidance and upgraded its FY25 distributable EPS to \(1\%\) growth from its original flat guidance. The modest earnings accretion came from its buyback, with the rising cost of debt \((+40\mathrm{bp}\) to \(4.7\%\) essentially eroding the \(3\%\) LFL NOI growth. The highlight in the result was the \(4.7\%\) increase in NTA to \(\) 2.89\(ps following\) 596\mathrm{m}(3.4\%)\(valuation gain. Aside from that, the result was in line with our expectations and had limited new news. WPR has completed\) \ \(32m\) of its planned \(\) 50m\(buyback and executed five divestments for a combined\) \ \(34.5\mathrm{m}\) at a \(1\%\) discount to Dec- 24 book value. 1H25 distributable earnings were \(\) 55.6\mathrm{m}(8.31\mathrm{eps})\) , up \(0.4\%\) on pcp and slightly ahead of our \(\) 54.6\mathrm{m}(8.19\mathrm{eps})\) . Operating metrics remain sound, WPR has maintained high occupancy at \(99.9\%\) , a low Management Expense Ratio at 30bps and has limited expirations \((- 3.9\%)\) over the next 18 months. WPR offers a secure income stream with a 6.6year WALE, trades at an \(8\%\) discount to NTA and a relatively high implied cap rate of \(5.97\%\) \((+31\mathrm{bp}\) on its current \(5.66\%\) WACR). Retain Neutral; \(\) 2.80\((+10e)\) Price Target.

Operating metrics in line with FY24: 1) WARR remain healthy at \(- 3\%\) driving \(3.0\%\) LFL rental growth in 1H; 2) The portfolio is full with \(99.9\%\) occupancy and the WALE remains long at 6.6 years, albeit continuing to reduce; and 3) the management expense ratio (MER) remains low at \(0.30\%\) .

Capital Management: WPR sold five non- core assets in 1H25 for a combined \(\) 34.5\mathrm{m}\(at a\) 1\%\(discount to Dec - 24 book values, all will settle in 2H. WPR noted it has a further seven non- core assets valued at\) \sim \$30\mathrm{m},\(which we expect it will divest over the next year or so. The divestments are being used to fund the current\) \ \(50\mathrm{m}\) buyback, \(\) 33\mathrm{m}\(of which was completed in 1H at an average price of\) \sim \$2.60\(, or a\) \sim 10\%\$ discount to its latest NTA. Pro forma liquidity is \(- \\(138m\), which is relatively elevated for WPR as it has retained funding capacity in the event of OTR conversion opportunities, however none have been forthcoming as yet and the process appears to be playing out over a longer time frame than originally expected. WPR's balance sheet remains in good shape with proforma gearing at \(32.5\%\) , providing capacity to expand the buyback and participate in potential future larger- scale OTR projects.

Guidance and earnings changes: WPR has raised its FY25 distributable EPS guidance from \(16.48\mathrm{eps}\) to \(16.64\mathrm{eps}\) . This implies \(1\%\) growth on FY24 compared with its prior flat guidance. Management noted its buyback hadn't been assumed in the original guidance which drove the upgrade. Underlying property growth ( \(3\%\) in 1H) is expected to be largely eroded by a rising average cost of debt, which was up \(40\mathrm{bp}\) in 1H to \(4.7\%\) . WPR is well hedged out to FY27 \((- 85\%)\) at a relatively stable hedged rate of \(2.9\%\) in 2H25 rising to \(3.2\%\) in FY27. The material move in its WACD happened in 1H. Earnings changes: We marginally increase our FY25 EPS by \(0.7\%\) , but lower FY26E and FY27E by \(- 0.3\%\) and \(- 1.6\%\) , respectively, as we model the \(\) 34.5\mathrm{m}\(of divestments and hedging restructuring for FY25 - 27.

WPR offers a stable income, underpinned by \(3\%\) fixed annual rent reviews, \(90\%\) triple net leases and no material near- term lease expiries. The first major lease expiries will start to come through in 2026. WPR has been amongst the most proactive REITs managing capital, selling non- core assets with higher releasing risk into strong transactional markets and using proceeds to buy back its discounted stock. It also has one of the lowest management expense ratios (MER) amongst the listed REITs at just 30bp. Gearing is at the lower end of WPR's target 30- 40% range. While we continue to view WPR's capital position as favourable, we see more favourable opportunities elsewhere given the stock's below- peer earnings growth prospects. We are also cognisant of the ESG headwinds the service station asset class faces over the medium term. Retain Neutral.

Our Jun- 26 price target of \(\) 2.80\(is based on the mid - point of our NAV and the roll - forward of our NPV. Our NAV assumes Jun - 25 property values decrease by\) 2\% \(. Our NPV is based on a five - year DCF of AFFO forecasts to which we apply a discount rate of\) 8.2\% \(, a terminal cap rate of\) 6.35\% \(reflecting a LT growth rate of\) 1.85\% \(. We use a\) 6.0\% \(market risk premium and\) 4.0\% \(risk- free rate.

WPR's portfolio comprises 400 service stations valued at \(2.9bn\) on a WACR of \(5.66\%\) (- 6bp in 1H). Metro assets account for the bulk of the portfolio \((81\%)\) and are valued at a WACR of \(5.36\%\) (- 7bp in 1H), with regional assets valued at a WACR of \(6.90\%\) (- 4bp in 1H). Cap rate compression and income growth drove a \(4.7\%\) increase in the NTA to \(2.89\mathrm{ps}\) . WPR is currently trading at a \(- 8\%\) discount to its Jun- 25 NTA, implying a \(5\%\) decline in book values or an implied cap rate of \(- 5.97\%\) .
Figure 1: WPR NTA and prem (disc) to NTA
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan.

Gearing remained flat at \(32.5\%\) , as positive revaluations of \(+3.4\%\) largely offset the \(- 533m\) of buyback in 1H. The buyback still has another \(- 517m\) to go, which will be funded through the \(34.5m\) of divestments set to settle in 2H. WPR has earmarked a further \(530m\) of assets as non- core. WPR has \(- 5120m\) of liquidity which could be utilised to fund any potential OTR conversions.
Figure 3: WPR gearing and gearing range
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan.

WPR has a relatively long 6.6- year WALE with no 2H expiries and \(3.8\%\) in FY26 (see Figure 5). The WALE has drifted down with the passage of time, but most leases have multiple 10- year options exercisable by the operators. \(81\%\) of WPR's service stations are on well- located metro sites with strong higher and better use potential, but unlocking this potential will 1) require existing leases to lapse without option exercise; and 2) site remediation.
Figure 2: WPR weighted average lease expiry (WALE)
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan.

WPR has upgraded its FY25 EPS to \(16.64\mathrm{eps}\) (Prev: \(16.48\mathrm{eps}\) ), representing \(1\%\) growth on FY24. Having offset the earnings drag driven by the step up in WACD through the current \(50m\) buyback program. We forecast EPS of \(16.7\mathrm{e}\) in FY25, which sits marginally ahead of WPR's guidance (16.64cps). Our DPS forecasts are in- line with EPS as we assume a \(100\%\) payout.
Figure 4: Our EPS/DPS forecasts
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates.

1H25 distributable earnings were \(\) 55.6m\(8.31 eps), up\) 0.4\% \(on pcp and slightly ahead of our\) \ \(54.6m\) (8.19eps). The beat was due to slightly higher rental income and lower interest expense than what we had forecast.
Table 2: 1H25 result vs pcp and our forecasts
Source: Company reports, J.P. Morgan estimates.

We revise our FY25, FY26 and FY27 distributable EPS estimates by \(+0.7\%\) \(- 0.3\%\) and \(- 1.6\%\) , respectively. Our FY25 EPS estimate of \(16.72eps\) sits marginally ahead of WPR's upgraded guidance of \(16.64eps\) . Key changes include:

- Divestment of assets: We modelled five assets set to settle in 2H25 worth a combined \(\) 34.5m\(at a\) 7.7\%\$ passing yield. This was a better than expected outcome at the FY24 result, with the assets divested being overrented. Updated hedging profile: We have updated our hedging profile to reflect the \(\) 100m\(of new interest rate swaps and\) \ \(200m\) of 'blend and extend' of existing swaps which materially lifted the hedge rate by \(+30bp\) and \(+70bp\) in FY27 and FY28.
